    "id": "TG07_Root_Mortality_Experiment_924_1",
    "stac_version": "1.1.0",
    "description": "We conducted an experiment on sand and clay tropical forest soils to test the short-term effect of root mortality on the soil-atmosphere flux of nitrous oxide, nitric oxide, methane, and carbon dioxide.  We induced root mortality by isolating blocks of land to 1 m using trenching and root exclusion screening.  Gas fluxes were measured weekly for ten weeks following the trenching treatment.  For nitrous oxide there was a highly significant increase in soil-atmosphere flux over the ten weeks following treatment for trenched plots compared to control plots.  N2O flux averaged 37.5 and 18.5 ng N cm-2 h-1 from clay trenched and control plots and 4.7 and 1.5 ng N cm-2 h-1 from sand trenched and control plots.  In contrast, there was no effect for soil-atmosphere flux of nitric oxide, carbon dioxide, or methane. ",
